stershire, England","Cheshire,, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bosworth Field, Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wintley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Windley, a place in Derbyshire named from Old English <i>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":43,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":52,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Wintley was born in 1506, in Cheshire, England, her father, Alexander Wintley, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Alexander Wintley, was 31. She married Richard Shenton in 1529, in Hinckley, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1560, in her hometown, at the age of 54, and was buried in Cheshire, England."},"et":{"1506–1560 ?":"1506–1560","1506–1560":"1506–1560","1505–1557":"1505–1557","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1480–1506":"1480–1506","1476–Female":"1476–Surnud","1560":"1560","1480":"1480","Abt 1504":"umbes 1504","Aft 1506":"pärast 1506","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","1529":"1529","1560 ?":"1560","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Shenton, Hinckley and Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hinckley, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, England","Cheshire,, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bosworth Field, Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1506–1560 ?":"1506–1560","1506–1560":"1506–1560","1505–1557":"1505–1557","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1480–1506":"1480–1506","1476–Female":"1476–Kuollut","1560":"1560","1480":"1480","Abt 1504":"noin 1504","Aft 1506":"1506 jälkeen","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","1529":"1529","1560 ?":"1560","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Shenton, Hinckley and Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Hinckley, Leicestershi